    {
      "index": 831,
      "id": "80254f24-e1ed-4764-9945-c088ce9c687c",
      "role": "assistant",
      "text": "What may fail first: **building a full autonomous agent too early**. With a 6GB GPU, Ollama is useful for **intent classification, summarizing logs, and proposing plans**, not for trusted autonomous execution. MCP should expose deterministic tools; the local model should propose tool use, not decide destructive actions. MCP architecture has three separate roles: the **host** is the app you interact with, the **client** is the protocol connection manager inside that host, and the **server** exposes tools/resources. Official MCP docs describe the host as coordinating clients, with each client handling one direct server connection. citeturn961601search6 Your `pb mcp serve` is already the **server**. What is missing is a **Promptbranch local host/client** that talks to Ollama and connects to that server. ## Continue in this order ### 1. Validate Ollama locally first Use small models. With 6GB VRAM, start with 3B or smaller. Ollama’s own library lists `qwen2.5-coder` in 0.5B, 1.5B, 3B, 7B, 14B, and 32B sizes, and `llama3.2` in 1B and 3B sizes. citeturn911185search0turn911185search1 Ollama also defaults to shorter context below 24GB VRAM, so do not design around huge context windows. citeturn961601search15 Run: ```bash ollama pull qwen2.5-coder:3b ollama pull llama3.2:3b ollama run qwen2.5-coder:3b 'Return only JSON: {\"intent\":\"inspect_repo\",\"risk\":\"read\"}' ``` If JSON discipline is poor, try: ```bash ollama run llama3.2:3b 'Return only JSON: {\"intent\":\"inspect_repo\",\"risk\":\"read\"}' ``` ### 2. Keep current Promptbranch MCP server read-only You already have: ```bash pb mcp serve --path . ``` That remains the tool server. Local MCP servers commonly use stdio transport for one client connection. citeturn961601search0 Do **not** add write tools yet. ### 3. Add a Promptbranch local host/client MVP The next release should implement this, narrowly: ```bash pb agent chat --path . --model qwen2.5-coder:3b pb agent ask \"inspect repo state\" --path . --model qwen2.5-coder:3b --json pb agent tool-call filesystem.read '{\"path\":\"VERSION\"}' --path . --json ``` Internal pieces: ```text pb agent host ├─ Ollama client ├─ MCP stdio client ├─ Promptbranch MCP server subprocess ├─ tool allowlist ├─ deterministic policy gate └─ transcript/log output ``` The host should spawn: ```bash promptbranch --profile-dir .pb_profile mcp serve --path . ``` Then speak JSON-RPC over stdio. ### 4. MVP behavior The first useful flow should be: ```bash pb agent ask \"What is the repo version and git status?\" --json ``` Expected deterministic sequence: 1. Ollama classifies intent: ```json {\"intent\":\"inspect_repo\",\"risk\":\"read\",\"tools\":[\"filesystem.read\",\"git.status\"]} ``` 2. Policy gate allows read-only tools. 3. MCP client calls: - `filesystem.read` with `VERSION` - `git.status` 4. Ollama summarizes the tool results. 5. Output includes both: - raw tool results - model summary ### 5. Hard safety boundary Allowed automatically: ```text filesystem.read filesystem.list git.status git.diff.summary promptbranch.state.read artifact.verify ``` Blocked for now: ```text src add src rm artifact release test execution shell execution git write operations ``` This matches the safer model: local LLM proposes JSON intent; deterministic executor validates; state updates happen only after verified outcomes. ## Recommended next release scope For `v0.0.142`, I would implement only: ```bash pb agent ask --path . --model qwen2.5-coder:3b --json pb agent tool-call <tool> <json-args> --path . --json pb agent models --json ``` Plus tests for: ```text MCP server subprocess starts initialize succeeds tools/list succeeds filesystem.read VERSION succeeds Ollama unavailable gives clean error write tool request is rejected ``` No write-capable MCP execution yet. ## Practical local test before coding Run this now: ```bash ollama list ollama run qwen2.5-coder:3b 'Return only JSON. Classify this request: \"read VERSION and git status\". Schema: {\"intent\":string,\"risk\":\"read|write\",\"tools\":[string]}' ``` Good enough output: ```json {\"intent\":\"inspect_repo\",\"risk\":\"read\",\"tools\":[\"filesystem.read\",\"git.status\"]} ``` Bad output: prose, markdown fences, invented tool names, or write actions. If bad, use Ollama only for summaries and make classification deterministic/rule-based. Confidence: medium-high. Verdict: ✅ Strengths — Promptbranch already has the MCP server; adding a local host/client is now a bounded engineering step. ⚠️ Weaknesses — 6GB VRAM limits model size and context; do not rely on the local model for complex autonomous coding. 🔍 Unknowns — which small Ollama model gives reliable JSON intent extraction on your machine. 🧩 Next step — test `qwen2.5-coder:3b` JSON discipline, then implement `pb agent ask` as a read-only MCP host/client wrapper around Ollama.",
