      "text": "Yes. Test it first. Your pulls succeeded, but the important part is still missing: **did `ollama run qwen2.5-coder:3b ...` return clean JSON only?** Run these: ```bash ollama list ollama run qwen2.5-coder:3b \\ 'Return only JSON. Classify this request: \"read VERSION and git status\". Schema: {\"intent\":string,\"risk\":\"read|write\",\"tools\":[string]}' ``` Good output: ```json {\"intent\":\"inspect_repo\",\"risk\":\"read\",\"tools\":[\"filesystem.read\",\"git.status\"]} ``` Bad output: ```text Sure, here is the JSON... ```json ... ``` ``` or invented tools. Also test Promptbranch MCP locally: ```bash pb mcp host-smoke --path . --json \\ 2>&1 | tee pb_mcp_host_smoke.v0.0.141.log ``` If both pass, then the next implementation step is safe: ```bash pb agent ask --path . --model qwen2.5-coder:3b --json ``` Critical assessment: Ollama is installed and models are downloaded, but that only proves availability. It does **not** prove JSON discipline or MCP integration. Confidence: high. Verdict: ✅ Strengths — models downloaded successfully. ⚠️ Weaknesses — no evidence yet that the model emits strict JSON. 🔍 Unknowns — whether `qwen2.5-coder:3b` or `llama3.2:3b` behaves better on your machine. 🧩 Next step — run the JSON classification test and `pb mcp host-smoke`.",
