      "role": "assistant",
      "text": "What may fail first: the word “agent” makes this look more autonomous than it is. In v0.0.142, the tested flow uses **no Ollama planning** and no ChatGPT/browser call. It is deterministic local tool execution through Promptbranch’s read-only MCP-style tools. ## What calls were used For: ```bash pb agent ask \"read VERSION and git status\" --path . --json ``` Promptbranch used: ```json { \"mode\": \"deterministic_read_only\", \"planner\": \"rule_based_v1\", \"tool_calls\": [ { \"name\": \"filesystem.read\", \"arguments\": { \"path\": \"VERSION\", \"max_bytes\": 2000 } }, { \"name\": \"git.status\", \"arguments\": {} } ] } ``` The log confirms both tool calls and also confirms Ollama was **not** used for planning or summary. fileciteturn40file0 So the equivalent low-level calls are: ```bash pb agent tool-call filesystem.read '{\"path\":\"VERSION\",\"max_bytes\":2000}' --path . --json pb agent tool-call git.status '{}' --path . --json ``` The direct `filesystem.read` reproduction already succeeded and returned `v0.0.142`. fileciteturn40file1 ## Which MCP tools exist The read-only MCP manifest exposes these 9 tools: ```text promptbranch.state.read promptbranch.workspace.current promptbranch.task.current filesystem.list filesystem.read git.status git.diff.summary artifact.registry.current artifact.verify ``` They are all read-only in the default manifest; write/destructive tools are not part of the default executable surface. fileciteturn40file2 ## Ollama calls used For the successful `pb agent ask ...` run: ```text Ollama planning: no Ollama summary: no Ollama model: null ``` The log explicitly says: ```json \"ollama\": { \"used_for_planning\": false, \"used_for_summary\": false, \"model\": null } ``` fileciteturn40file0 So the only Ollama-related command you ran was: ```bash pb agent models --json ``` That checks Ollama availability/model inventory. It does not drive tool selection. ## Reproduce from command line ### 1. Reproduce the high-level agent command ```bash pb agent ask \"read VERSION and git status\" --path . --json \\ | jq . ``` ### 2. Reproduce each tool call directly ```bash pb agent tool-call filesystem.read '{\"path\":\"VERSION\",\"max_bytes\":2000}' --path . --json \\ | jq . ``` ```bash pb agent tool-call git.status '{}' --path . --json \\ | jq . ``` ### 3. Reproduce available MCP tools ```bash pb mcp manifest --json \\ | jq '.tools[].name' ``` ### 4. Reproduce through raw MCP stdio JSON-RPC This bypasses `pb agent` and talks to `pb mcp serve` directly: ```bash printf '%s\\n' \\ '{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"id\":1,\"method\":\"initialize\",\"params\":{}}' \\ '{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"id\":2,\"method\":\"tools/list\",\"params\":{}}' \\ '{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"id\":3,\"method\":\"tools/call\",\"params\":{\"name\":\"filesystem.read\",\"arguments\":{\"path\":\"VERSION\",\"max_bytes\":2000}}}' \\ '{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"id\":4,\"method\":\"tools/call\",\"params\":{\"name\":\"git.status\",\"arguments\":{}}}' \\ | pb mcp serve --path . ``` To pretty-print newline-delimited JSON: ```bash printf '%s\\n' \\ '{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"id\":1,\"method\":\"initialize\",\"params\":{}}' \\ '{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"id\":2,\"method\":\"tools/list\",\"params\":{}}' \\ '{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"id\":3,\"method\":\"tools/call\",\"params\":{\"name\":\"filesystem.read\",\"arguments\":{\"path\":\"VERSION\",\"max_bytes\":2000}}}' \\ '{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"id\":4,\"method\":\"tools/call\",\"params\":{\"name\":\"git.status\",\"arguments\":{}}}' \\ | pb mcp serve --path . \\ | while read -r line; do echo \"$line\" | jq .; done ``` ## Minimal mental model ```text pb agent ask ↓ rule-based planner ↓ filesystem.read VERSION git.status ↓ JSON result ``` Not this: ```text pb agent ask ↓ Ollama decides tools ↓ MCP executes ``` That second design is intentionally blocked for now because your local models produced unreliable/invalid JSON. Confidence: high. Verdict: ✅ Strengths — fully reproducible with direct CLI and raw JSON-RPC; no