      "index": 923,
      "id": "9db89946-6ae4-4bc0-aa70-8b5e22b61c62",
      "role": "assistant",
      "text": "Understood. We should **not depend on Cursor or Claude Desktop as the MCP host**. For Promptbranch, the correct architecture is: ```text Promptbranch local host ├─ MCP client manager ├─ Ollama model adapter ├─ deterministic policy gate └─ one or more MCP server connections └─ pb mcp serve --path <repo> ``` Cursor/Claude Desktop can be useful as **reference implementations or compatibility test targets**, but not as architectural dependencies. ## What MCP actually gives us MCP has a host/client/server architecture: the **host** manages user interaction and multiple MCP client connections; each **client** connects to one MCP server; each **server** exposes tools/resources/prompts. The official spec describes this host-client-server architecture and JSON-RPC-based protocol. citeturn727742search13 So for Promptbranch: ```text Promptbranch = host Promptbranch MCP client = client pb mcp serve = server Ollama = model used by the host ``` That is exactly the architecture we should build. ## Can we use Cursor/Claude MCP “for free” or “as open source”? ### Cursor Cursor supports MCP configuration and can connect to MCP servers. citeturn727742search10 But Cursor itself is a commercial product with usage-limited free tiers and paid plans. Its pricing page describes paid self-serve plans; third-party pricing summaries also describe a free/hobby tier with limits. citeturn699169search2turn699169search3 Cursor is **not a good architectural base** for us because it is not our host, not under our control, and not open-source in the sense needed to rebuild its host/client internals. A Cursor forum answer explicitly says Cursor is not open-source even though it is based on VS Code. citeturn699169search23 ### Claude Desktop Claude Desktop can connect to local MCP servers; official MCP docs use Claude Desktop as an example local MCP client/host. citeturn727742search1 Anthropic’s support docs also describe local MCP servers and desktop extensions. citeturn699169search10 But for your Linux setup, Claude Desktop is a poor dependency: Claude Code docs state the desktop app is not available on Linux and says to use the CLI instead. citeturn699169search13 There are unofficial Linux repackaging projects, but that is not a clean engineering dependency. citeturn699169search5 ### MCP itself MCP is the open piece. The official Python SDK says it implements the full MCP spec, can build both clients and servers, and supports transports including stdio, SSE, and Streamable HTTP. citeturn727742search12 The official TypeScript SDK is also open source, with new code under Apache-2.0 and existing code under MIT. citeturn727742search6 So the answer is: ```text Use MCP protocol/SDKs: yes Use Cursor/Claude host as dependency: no Use Cursor/Claude as reference/test target: optional ``` ## Recommended Promptbranch architecture Build our own local host: ```text pb agent host ├─ reads user request ├─ calls Ollama for optional reasoning / proposal ├─ validates proposal deterministically ├─ opens MCP client connection(s) ├─ calls pb mcp serve tools ├─ returns structured result └─ logs every step ``` Initial transport: ```text stdio JSON-RPC ``` Reason: it is simple, local, and already implemented in `pb mcp serve`. Later optional transport: ```text Streamable HTTP ``` Reason: useful for multi-process/multi-client workflows, but more moving parts. ## What we should implement next Do **not** clone Cursor/Claude behavior. Implement a minimal Promptbranch-native host/client: ```bash pb agent host-smoke --path . --json pb agent mcp-call filesystem.read '{\"path\":\"VERSION\"}' --path . --json pb agent ollama-propose \"read VERSION\" --model llama3.2:3b --json pb agent run \"read VERSION\" --path . --model llama3.2:3b --json ``` Internal rule: ```text Ollama proposes. Promptbranch validates. MCP executes. Promptbranch reports. ``` For safety, keep writes blocked. ## Answer to your core question Yes, I understand: **we define our own architecture on the host where Promptbranch is running**. We should not rely on Cursor or Claude Desktop. They are useful external hosts, but they are not the system we are building. The open-source part we should rely on is the MCP protocol and SDKs, not proprietary host products. Confidence: high. Verdict: ✅ Strengths — building our own host gives full control over policy, logging, deterministic validation, and local Ollama behavior. ⚠️ Weaknesses — we must implement client/session handling ourselves instead of outsourcing it to Cursor/Claude. 🔍 Unknowns — whether stdio remains enough, or whether Promptbranch eventually needs Streamable HTTP for multi-client workflows. 🧩 Next step — add `pb agent host-smoke` / `pb agent run` as a Promptbranch-native MCP host/client loop, using Ollama only as a proposal source and keeping MCP execution read-only.",
      "create_time": 1777749453.236039
