      "index": 928,
      "id": "eb6a2779-f5ee-4a59-a8b4-d33d0368a90f",
      "role": "assistant",
      "text": "Understood. I investigated “skills” in the MCP/agent ecosystem. The short version: **skills are not MCP servers**. They are usually **portable instruction/workflow packages** that teach an agent *how to use tools*, while MCP servers expose the actual *tools/data/actions*. A skill may reference an MCP server, install alongside one, or even be distributed through MCP, but it is a different abstraction. ## What “skills” means A **skill** is typically a folder/package containing: ```text SKILL.md references/ scripts/ assets/ metadata/config ``` The MCP docs describe Agent Skills as portable instruction sets that give AI coding assistants domain knowledge for a task. For MCP development specifically, skills encode design decisions such as deployment model, tool patterns, and auth so an agent can scaffold the correct server. The reference MCP development plugin ships skills as `SKILL.md` plus a `references/` folder. citeturn260477view0 OpenAI’s Codex skills model is similar: local skills live in folders, and reusable skills can be distributed as plugins. OpenAI’s docs also say plugins can bundle skills together with MCP server configuration and presentation assets. citeturn260477view1 ## Skill vs MCP server Think of it like this: ```text MCP server = executable/service exposing tools = \"what can be called\" Skill = instructions/workflow/context = \"how and when to use the tools\" ``` Example: ```text MCP server: filesystem.read git.status artifact.verify Skill: \"When investigating a repo, first read VERSION, then git.status, then inspect recent logs, then summarize risk.\" ``` That distinction matters for Promptbranch. Your MCP server gives local deterministic capabilities. A skill would teach the host/agent how to orchestrate those capabilities safely. ## Why people say “download skills” There are now several ways skills are distributed: 1. **Manual skill folders** Copy a `SKILL.md` folder into the agent’s skills directory. 2. **Plugin/marketplace install** Claude Code-style and Codex-style plugins can install skills. MCP’s Agent Skills page shows install methods such as Claude Code plugin install, Vercel Skills CLI, and manual cloning/copying. citeturn260477view3 3. **Skills bundled with app/tool integration** OpenAI says plugins can bundle skills plus MCP server configuration. That means one package can include “how to use it” and “how to connect to tools.” citeturn260477view1 4. **Skills served over MCP** This is experimental but important. The `experimental-ext-skills` repo explains that MCP servers give agents tools, but tools alone are insufficient for complex workflows; skills provide structured “how-to” knowledge. It explicitly argues that a remote MCP server can serve both its tools and the instructions for using them. citeturn260477view2 FastMCP already has utilities for discovering and downloading skills from MCP servers that expose them, including `list_skills()`, `download_skill()`, and `sync_skills()`. citeturn260477view4 ## Relationship to Promptbranch For our architecture, the clean model should be: ```text Promptbranch host ├─ MCP client manager ├─ MCP servers │ ├─ filesystem/git/artifact/promptbranch tools ├─ Skill registry │ ├─ local SKILL.md packages │ ├─ downloaded skills │ └─ optional skills served over MCP ├─ policy gate └─ Ollama proposal/summarization layer ``` A Promptbranch skill should **not execute directly**. It should only influence planning. Bad design: ```text skill says run command → command runs ``` Good design: ```text skill suggests workflow → planner proposes tool calls → policy gate validates → MCP executes allowed tools ``` ## Example Promptbranch skill A future skill could look like: ```text skills/repo-inspection/SKILL.md ``` with content like: ```markdown --- name: repo-inspection description: Inspect a repository using read-only MCP tools. allowed_tools: - filesystem.read - git.status - git.diff.summary --- When asked to inspect a repository: 1. Read VERSION if present. 2. Run git.status. 3. If dirty, run git.diff.summary. 4. Report version, branch, dirty state, and risk. 5. Never call write tools. ``` That skill teaches the host *how to use* the existing MCP tools. It does not replace the MCP server. ## What we should build next For Promptbranch, I would add a **Skill layer**, not copy Claude/Codex blindly. Minimal commands: ```bash pb skill list pb skill show <name> pb skill install <path-or-url> pb skill sync <mcp-server> pb skill validate <path> pb agent run --skill repo-inspection \"inspect this repo\" ``` Minimal internal structure: ```text .promptbranch/skills/ repo-inspection/ SKILL.md references/ ``` or global: ```text ~/.config/promptbranch/skills/ ``` Critical rule: skills should be parsed and validated before use. Unknown tools, write tools, or vague destructive instructions should be rejected. ## Should Promptbranch support “skills over MCP”? Eventually, yes. But not first. Order should be: 1. Local skill registry from folders. 2. Skill validation. 3. Skill-guided deterministic read-only planning. 4. Optional skill download/import. 5. Skills exposed/consumed over MCP. The reason: “skills over MCP” is still experimental. The MCP working group repo explicitly describes current gaps such as no standard discovery mechanism and complex workflows exceeding practical instruction size. citeturn260477view2 ## Practical conclusion Skills are useful for Promptbranch, but they are **not the same thing as downloadable MCP servers**. Use this mental model: ```text MCP server = capability Skill = operating procedure Host = policy + orchestration Ollama = optional reasoning/summarization ``` For Promptbranch, the next strong architecture step is: ```text Add pb skill registry → bind skills to allowed MCP tools → use skills to guide pb agent run → keep all execution policy-gated ``` Confidence: high. Verdict: ✅ Strengths — skills fit Promptbranch well because they encode repeatable workflows without giving the model direct execution power. ⚠️ Weaknesses — the ecosystem uses “skills” inconsistently; Claude, Codex, FastMCP, and MCP experimental extensions are related but not identical. 🔍 Unknowns — whether “skills over MCP” will stabilize as a standard distribution mechanism or remain implementation-specific. 🧩 Next step — implement `pb skill list/show/validate` locally first, then wire one `repo-inspection` skill to the existing read-only MCP tools.",
      "create_time": 1777749982.232233
    },
