      "id": "f76eade3-cb51-428b-9a45-923f9723652d",
      "role": "assistant",
      "text": "Your first try is a useful result, but it is **not evidence that Ollama is trustworthy yet**. What failed: - `llama3.2:3b` - schema mode produced invalid JSON with repetitive garbage. - tool mode produced no tool call. - `qwen2.5-coder:3b` - schema mode invented a disallowed `python` tool. - tool mode produced repeated prose and no tool call. - `qwen3:8b` - schema mode invented tool `\"1\"`. - tool mode produced no tool call. So the current verdict is: ```text Ollama service works ✅ Models respond ✅ Model-proposed MCP tool calls reliable ❌ Promptbranch validation correctly rejects bad proposals ✅ ``` There is one harness weakness worth fixing before we conclude too strongly: the first version exposed **dotted MCP names** like `filesystem.read` directly to the model. Small local models often handle simpler function names better, which is closer to the `ai-aip` / LangChain style. I created a v2 harness that uses simple model-facing aliases: ```text read_file -> filesystem.read git_status -> git.status git_diff_summary -> git.diff.summary ``` Download: [ollama_mcp_verification_harness_v2.zip](sandbox:/mnt/data/ollama_mcp_verification_harness_v2.zip) Run: ```bash unzip ollama_mcp_verification_harness_v2.zip cd ollama_mcp_verification_harness_v2 python3 verify_ollama_mcp_trust_v2.py \\ --repo-path /home/spikkie/git/chatgpt_claudecode_workflow \\ --models llama3.2:3b qwen2.5-coder:3b qwen3:8b \\ --prompt \"read VERSION\" \\ --execute-first-valid ``` Optional LangChain-style test: ```bash python3 -m pip install langchain-ollama langchain-core python3 verify_ollama_mcp_trust_v2.py \\ --repo-path /home/spikkie/git/chatgpt_claudecode_workflow \\ --models llama3.2:3b qwen2.5-coder:3b qwen3:8b \\ --try-langchain \\ --execute-first-valid ``` Critical assessment: - Your first result supports the current safety rule: **Ollama proposals must be validated and must fail closed**. - v2 is a fairer test because it uses simpler tool aliases and maps them back to MCP names after validation. - If v2 still fails, we should stop trying to use these local models for planning and keep them summary-only until a better model/prompt/tool-binding method is found. Confidence: high. Verdict: ✅ Strengths — the validation layer is doing its job; no bad model output reached MCP execution. ⚠️ Weaknesses — all three tested models failed proposal quality in v1. 🔍 Unknowns — whether alias-based tool names or LangChain binding improves behavior. 🧩 Next step — run the v2 harness with `--execute-first-valid` and upload the JSON output.",
