      "id": "1bb698eb-972c-421f-bd2c-365cd9750f7e",
      "role": "assistant",
      "text": "Yes. We can use a better model, and your current results strongly suggest we should. What may fail first: your **6GB VRAM** is the constraint. A better tool-calling model may run, but slower and partly on CPU. That is acceptable for verification, but probably not for a smooth agent loop yet. ## Better models to try Start with models that Ollama marks as tool-capable. Ollama’s docs say it supports tool/function calling through the chat API, and its model library marks tool-capable models with a `tools` capability. citeturn217472search3turn217472search8 ### Best first candidate ```bash ollama pull llama3.1:8b ``` Reason: Ollama’s own tool-support announcement uses Llama 3.1 as a tool-calling example, and the library lists `llama3.1:8b` with `tools`. citeturn217472search5turn217472search2 ### Also worth testing ```bash ollama pull llama3-groq-tool-use:8b ``` Reason: this model is explicitly described in Ollama’s library as built for tool/function calling. citeturn217472search10 ### Coding model, but not necessarily best for tools ```bash ollama pull qwen2.5-coder:7b ``` Reason: Qwen2.5-Coder 7B should be better than your 3B version for code reasoning, but “coding ability” is not the same as reliable tool calling. Ollama lists Qwen2.5-Coder sizes including 7B, 14B, and 32B. citeturn217472search1 ## Test command Run v2 harness with the better tool models: ```bash python3 verify_ollama_mcp_trust_v2.py \\ --repo-path /home/spikkie/git/chatgpt_claudecode_workflow \\ --models llama3.1:8b llama3-groq-tool-use:8b qwen2.5-coder:7b \\ --prompt \"read VERSION\" \\ --execute-first-valid ``` If 8B is too slow, test one model at a time: ```bash python3 verify_ollama_mcp_trust_v2.py \\ --repo-path /home/spikkie/git/chatgpt_claudecode_workflow \\ --models llama3.1:8b \\ --prompt \"read VERSION\" \\ --execute-first-valid ``` ## My ranking for your purpose ```text 1. llama3.1:8b best first test for native Ollama tools 2. llama3-groq-tool-use:8b likely good for function/tool calls 3. qwen2.5-coder:7b better coder, uncertain tool discipline 4. qwen3:8b already failed v1; retest only with aliases 5. llama3.2:3b too weak/unstable for tool planning 6. qwen2.5-coder:3b failed badly ``` ## Practical decision rule Use a model for planning only if it repeatedly returns: ```json { \"alias_tool\": \"read_file\", \"mcp_tool\": \"filesystem.read\", \"arguments\": { \"path\": \"VERSION\" } } ``` and MCP execution succeeds. One good run is not enough. Minimum test matrix: ```bash for p in \"read VERSION\" \"show git status\" \"inspect repo\"; do python3 verify_ollama_mcp_trust_v2.py \\ --repo-path /home/spikkie/git/chatgpt_claudecode_workflow \\ --models llama3.1:8b \\ --prompt \"$p\" \\ --execute-first-valid done ``` Confidence: medium-high. Verdict: ✅ Strengths — better tool-capable 8B models exist and are worth testing. ⚠️ Weaknesses — 6GB VRAM may make 8B models slow or partly CPU-bound. 🔍 Unknowns — whether `llama3.1:8b` or `llama3-groq-tool-use:8b` behaves better on your hardware. 🧩 Next step — pull `llama3.1:8b` first and run the v2 harness against `read VERSION`.",
