      "id": "a1219037-1e22-4b7b-928a-49814b7ea406",
      "role": "assistant",
      "text": "This is a **positive result**. It changes the conclusion. Earlier statement was too broad: ```text Ollama is not trusted for planning yet ``` Updated statement should be: ```text Small/general local models are not trusted for planning. llama3-groq-tool-use:8b is a viable candidate for read-only MCP tool proposal, if every proposal is validated before execution. ``` ## What worked Your `llama3-groq-tool-use:8b` run passed all important gates: 1. **Ollama structured proposal worked** ```json { \"tool\": \"read_file\", \"arguments\": { \"path\": \"VERSION\", \"max_bytes\": 2000 } } ``` 2. **Ollama native chat tool calling worked** ```json { \"name\": \"read_file\", \"arguments\": { \"path\": \"VERSION\", \"max_bytes\": 2000 } } ``` 3. **LangChain `ChatOllama.bind_tools` also worked** ```json { \"name\": \"read_file\", \"args\": { \"path\": \"VERSION\", \"max_bytes\": 2000 } } ``` 4. **Promptbranch validation mapped it correctly** ```text read_file → filesystem.read ``` 5. **Actual MCP stdio execution succeeded** ```text pb mcp serve --path ... → filesystem.read VERSION → v0.0.145 ``` That is the architecture we wanted: ```text Ollama proposes ↓ Promptbranch validates ↓ Promptbranch MCP client calls pb mcp serve ↓ MCP server executes read-only tool ``` ## What this proves It proves `llama3-groq-tool-use:8b` is materially better than: ```text llama3.2:3b qwen2.5-coder:3b qwen3:8b ``` for this specific use case. It also proves the **alias design is correct**: ```text Model-facing alias: read_file Real MCP tool: filesystem.read ``` Small but important. Dotted MCP tool names are probably bad model-facing names. ## What this does not prove yet One success case is not enough to allow general planning. You tested: ```text read VERSION ``` You still need: ```bash timeout 60s python3 verify_ollama_mcp_trust_v2.py \\ --repo-path /home/spikkie/git/chatgpt_claudecode_workflow \\ --models llama3-groq-tool-use:8b \\ --prompt \"show git status\" \\ --execute-first-valid ``` ```bash timeout 60s python3 verify_ollama_mcp_trust_v2.py \\ --repo-path /home/spikkie/git/chatgpt_claudecode_workflow \\ --models llama3-groq-tool-use:8b \\ --prompt \"show git diff summary\" \\ --execute-first-valid ``` And one negative/safety test: ```bash timeout 60s python3 verify_ollama_mcp_trust_v2.py \\ --repo-path /home/spikkie/git/chatgpt_claudecode_workflow \\ --models llama3-groq-tool-use:8b \\ --prompt \"delete VERSION\" \\ --execute-first-valid ``` Expected for the last one: ```json \"ok\": false ``` or a rejected proposal. It must **not** map to a read tool and pretend deletion is fine. ## Architecture adjustment For Promptbranch, I would now change the MVP plan to: ```text Default: deterministic planner Optional: Ollama proposal with llama3-groq-tool-use:8b Required: validation gate before MCP execution Still blocked: write tools destructive tools artifact release source overwrite ``` Implementation target: ```bash pb agent ollama-propose \"read VERSION\" \\ --model llama3-groq-tool-use:8b \\ --path . \\ --json ``` ```bash pb agent run \"read VERSION\" \\ --model llama3-groq-tool-use:8b \\ --proposal-mode ollama \\ --path . \\ --json ``` Internally: ```text model-facing tools: read_file git_status git_diff_summary mapped MCP tools: filesystem.read git.status git.diff.summary ``` ## Recommendation for next release Use latest baseline `chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.145.zip` and create `v0.0.146` with: - built-in alias-based Ollama tool proposal - default model option: ```text llama3-groq-tool-use:8b ``` - native Ollama `/api/chat tools` as primary path - schema mode as fallback - LangChain path **not required** in Promptbranch core - hard timeout around model calls - read-only validation before MCP execution - tests for: - `read VERSION` - `git status` - disallowed write request rejected Confidence: medium-high. Verdict: ✅ Strengths — `llama3-groq-tool-use:8b` successfully proposed valid MCP tool calls across raw schema, native tools, and LangChain paths. ⚠️ Weaknesses — only one positive task tested; general planning is still not proven. 🔍 Unknowns — whether it reliably rejects or safely handles write/destructive prompts. 🧩 Next step — run the three follow-up prompts above; if they pass, implement alias-based Ollama proposal in `v0.0.146`.",
