      "index": 1097,
      "id": "6a00501b-e80c-4da8-a09a-90baa8a15b57",
      "role": "assistant",
      "text": "What may fail first: **calling the current state “agentic” too broadly**. The MVP is currently a constrained, read-only local agent shell. That is the correct foundation, but it is not yet a write-capable coding agent. ## MVP summary so far ### Core architecture Promptbranch is now moving toward this architecture: ```text User ↓ Promptbranch CLI / local host ├─ deterministic planner ├─ policy gate ├─ optional Ollama proposal layer ├─ local skill registry ├─ MCP client └─ MCP server: pb mcp serve --path <repo> └─ read-only repo/git/state/artifact tools ``` This matches the intended direction: Promptbranch becomes its own MCP host/client instead of depending on Cursor or Claude Desktop. The source model also says Promptbranch should be the local control plane, ChatGPT.com remains the project/task execution surface, MCP provides deterministic tools, Ollama is optional, and skills are reusable procedures. fileciteturn54file4 ## Implemented and validated ### 1. Read-only MCP server Implemented: ```bash pb mcp manifest --json pb mcp serve --path . pb mcp config --path . --json pb mcp host-smoke --path . --json ``` Read-only MCP tools: ```text promptbranch.state.read promptbranch.workspace.current promptbranch.task.current filesystem.list filesystem.read git.status git.diff.summary artifact.registry.current artifact.verify ``` These tools are deterministic local capabilities. Write tools remain blocked. ### 2. Promptbranch-native MCP host/client loop Implemented and validated in `v0.0.148`: ```bash pb agent host-smoke --path . --json pb agent mcp-call filesystem.read '{\"path\":\"VERSION\"}' --path . --json pb agent run \"read VERSION and git status\" --path . --json ``` The tested path is: ```text pb agent run ↓ planner ↓ policy gate ↓ MCP stdio client ↓ pb mcp serve ↓ filesystem.read + git.status ↓ structured result ``` Your logs showed this works: `filesystem.read` returned `VERSION = v0.0.148`, `git.status` returned clean repo state on `main`, and execution went through MCP stdio. fileciteturn62file0 fileciteturn62file1 ### 3. Local skill registry Implemented and validated: ```bash pb skill list --json pb skill validate .promptbranch/skills/repo-inspection --json pb agent run --skill repo-inspection \"inspect repo\" --path . --json ``` Built-in skill: ```text repo-inspection ``` Skill procedure: ```text 1. read VERSION 2. run git.status 3. run git.diff.summary if needed 4. report version, branch, SHA, dirty state, and risk ``` The skill validation passed with no unknown tools and no write tools. The skill-guided run executed `filesystem.read`, `git.status`, and `git.diff.summary` through MCP stdio. fileciteturn64file14 fileciteturn62file2 ### 4. Ollama proposal path We tested several models. Bad candidates: ```text llama3.2:3b qwen2.5-coder:3b qwen3:8b ``` They produced invalid JSON, no tool calls, or wrong tools. Good candidate: ```text llama3-groq-tool-use:8b ``` It successfully proposed tool calls using model-facing aliases: ```text read_file → filesystem.read git_status → git.status git_diff_summary → git.diff.summary ``` In `v0.0.146+`, Promptbranch added deterministic request-risk classification before executing any model proposal. Validated behavior: ```bash pb agent mcp-llm-smoke \"read VERSION\" --path . --model llama3-groq-tool-use:8b --json ``` succeeds, while: ```bash pb agent mcp-llm-smoke \"delete VERSION\" --path . --model llama3-groq-tool-use:8b --json ``` fails closed before MCP execution. In `v0.0.148`, `pb agent run \"delete VERSION\"` also correctly returned `risk_rejected`, with no plan and no tool execution. fileciteturn65file15 ## Safety model now in place Current auto-allowed risk level: ```text read ``` Current blocked categories: ```text write destructive broad shell execution source sync/add/remove through agent artifact release through agent git write operations project source overwrite ``` This matches the MVP plan: every layer must be independently testable, Ollama failure must not break deterministic tool calls, and write tools must reject by default. fileciteturn54file6 ## Current state by version ```text v0.0.139 MCP stdio server v0.0.140 MCP config and smoke suite v0.0.141 host-smoke / absolute-path host config v0.0.142 deterministic read-only agent ask/tool-call v0.0.143 first Ollama-proposed MCP smoke v0.0.146 alias-based Ollama proposal + request risk gate v0.0.147 parser fix + project_endpoint visibility fix v0.0.148 pb agent run + mcp-call + skill registry + repo-inspection skill ``` ## MVP acceptance status ### Done ```text MCP server works without Ollama MCP client/host loop works without external hosts Agent works without ChatGPT/browser Read-only tool execution works through stdio Ollama proposal can succeed with llama3-groq-tool-use:8b Invalid/destructive request fails closed Local skill validation works Skill-guided read-only execution works ``` ### Not done ```text controlled process/test execution artifact/source writes through agent remote skill downloads skills-over-MCP HTTP MCP transport broad shell execution autonomous coding/editing transactional agent-controlled source sync transactional artifact release ``` ## Current MVP definition The MVP now proven is: ```text Promptbranch-native local read-only agent shell → deterministic or skill-guided planning → optional Ollama proposal for read-only calls → policy gate → MCP stdio client → pb mcp serve → structured tool results ``` Not yet: ```text write-capable coding agent ``` ## Recommended next MVP step Implement **controlled process execution**, not source/artifact writes yet. Narrow next tool: ```text test.smoke ``` Target commands: ```bash pb agent tool-call test.smoke '{}' --path . --json pb agent run \"run smoke tests\" --path . --json ``` Required behavior: ```text timeout required stdout/stderr captured exit code captured no arbitrary shell command no cleanup/destructive action no source/project mutation ``` This is the next logical step from read-only inspection to controlled execution without opening the door to arbitrary shell writes. ## Verdict ✅ Strengths — The read-only MCP host/client loop is proven; local skills work; `llama3-groq-tool-use:8b` can propose safe read-only calls when guarded; destructive requests fail closed. ⚠️ Weaknesses — The system is not yet a write-capable agent; process execution is still missing; artifact/source mutations remain intentionally blocked. 🔍 Unknowns — Whether controlled test execution can be constrained without becoming arbitrary shell execution; whether Ollama remains stable on broader read-only tasks. 🧩 Next step — Add `test.smoke` as a controlled process MCP tool and wire `pb agent run \"run smoke tests\"` to it.",
